<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Ivory Coast</TITLE>
<H2>IVORY COAST</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>The West African country of Ivory Coast became a French colony in 1893. From 1904 to 
1958, it was part of the Federation of French West Africa, a group of West African French 
colonies. It gained independence from France in 1960. Until his recent death, President Felix 
Houphouet-Boigny ruled the country with little regard for free market reform or democracy. 
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">   
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Ivory Coast has very high tariffs, with an average tariff rate of 36.2 percent. <FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>
   Non-tariff barriers exist in the form of import taxes and strict labeling requirements.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Ivory Coast has moderately high taxes. Its top income tax rate is 60 percent, with average 
income being taxed at 10 percent. The top corporate income tax level is 35 percent. 
Moreover, the Ivory Coast maintains a 35 percent capital gains tax, a 25 percent value-
added tax, and a turnover tax from 10 percent to 25 percent on services and interest 
provided by banks and financial companies.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The government consumes 31.2 percent of GDP. Ivory Coast has a significant state-owned 
sector that contributes to a majority of the GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Its average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 3.8 percent. It was 0.5 percent in 1992.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Despite government overtures, foreign investors remain wary because of crime, corruption, an 
inefficient and abusive bureaucracy, and unstable legal protections. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
The financial system is heavily regulated by the government. For example, banks still remain 
under the heavy control of government. However, the government has made credit reforms 
which have made it easier for private companies to get loans.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Economic activities are highly regulated through a web of government-imposed price controls. 
The government has made some progress toward liberalizing prices. The Ivory Coast 
maintains a minimum wage law.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Property is at risk in the Ivory Coast since expropriation remains possible. The court system, 
although made much more efficient than in the past, is still unable to protect private 
property adequately.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
The bureaucracy is corrupt, and companies sometimes find it difficult to obtain a license to 
open a business. The government has tried to reduce the bureaucratic barriers to business 
by making it easier for businesses to conform to government regulations. However, there 
has not been sufficient progress in this area.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The high trade barriers in the Ivory Coast make smuggling of many items, mainly consumer 
goods, a lucrative business.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.25</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This figure is based on the most recent IMF figures available. The average tariff rate is derived 
from calculating 1989 taxes on international trade as a percentage of total imports.
</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
