<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Jamaica</TITLE>
<H2>JAMAICA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Caribbean island nation of Jamaica has seldom adopted a free market approach to 
economic policy. During the 1970s and part of the 1980s, the government was the primary player in 
the economy. Entrepreneurship was not encouraged, and Jamaica was on its way to developing a 
socialist economy. Until recently, Jamaica's economy was mostly not free. It was characterized by 
a high level of protectionism and government intervention in the economy. However, the 
government recently has opened up the economy to foreign investments and has reduced taxes. 
While Jamaica's economy has grown slowly in the past, the prospects for future economic growth 
look good.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Jamaica has tariff rates that range from 5 percent to 45 percent. Its average tariff rate is over 10 percent. 
<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>
   Import licenses are required for motor vehicles, certain chemicals, pharmaceuticals, onions, 
tomatoes, and other items. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Jamaica has a top marginal income tax rate of 25 percent. The tax on the average income level 
is 25 percent. Jamaica has a top marginal corporate tax rate of 33.33 percent. Jamaica also 
has a consumption tax of up to 12.5 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Jamaica's government consumption figure as a percentage of GDP is 11.6 percent, down from 
around 20 percent in 1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of inflation)</I><BR>
Jamaica had an average annual inflation rate of 19.6 percent between 1980 and 1991. Inflation 
increased to 75 percent in 1992.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Jamaica encourages foreign investment in nearly all areas. It provides some incentives to 
investors who use Jamaican raw materials and supplies. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Jamaica has a mixture of domestic and foreign banks. There are few direct restrictions on the 
formation of banks, and the government has reduced its control of the financial system. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls remain on many items, including bus fares, kerosene, and sugar. Jamaica has a 
minimum wage law. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
The chance of expropriation in Jamaica is remote. Private property, however, is not a fully 
recognized right. There have been some instances of property being confiscated.
 <P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
Most regulations pose a moderate burden on business. Bribery and corruption exist.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Smuggling is big business in Jamaica because prices remain high in many areas like consumer 
electronics. Pirated broadcasts, video tapes, and recorded music are frequent products on 
the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.80</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 2  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Jamaica receives about 14 percent of its revenues from duties on imports. With revenues of 
about $1.2 billion, revenues from duties equal about $168 million, which alone equals over 9 percent of 
total imports.
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
