<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Jordan</TITLE>
<H2>JORDAN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Jordan became an independent country in 1946. It has been ruled by the Hashemite 
monarchy ever since. Jordan began a series of economic reforms in 1988 to correct lagging growth 
rates. Jordan is attempting to reduce its budget deficit through controlled spending, reduced 
subsidies and tariffs, and lower taxes. Still, Jordan maintains many policies that limit its people's 
economic freedom. These policies continue to plague Jordan's economy.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Jordan has an average tariff rate of 12.9 percent. It has particularly high taxes on items like 
automobiles which range from 110 percent to 310 percent. Jordan's customs procedures 
are plagued by bureaucracy and often pose a barrier to imports. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Jordan has a top marginal income tax rate of 45 percent. The average income level is taxed at a 
rate of 5 percent. Jordan has a top corporate tax rate of 55 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Jordan's government consumption figure as percentage of GDP is 38.4 percent.<FONT 
SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Jordan had an annual average inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 1.6 percent.  Through most 
of 1994  inflation hovered around 5 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Jordan maintains few restrictions on foreign investment. However, industries deemed to be vital 
to national security, such as utilities, are not open to outside investors. Moreover, there are 
some ownership restrictions on trade and transportation industries. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Foreigners are allowed to invest in Jordanian banks. The government maintains some control 
over banks through strict reserve requirements.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
The government sets prices on such items as "non-strategic food commodities" and "non-food 
commodities." For example, it rations some goods such as sugar, rice, and milk, and it 
subsidizes prices of basic foodstuffs such as cereals, sugar, milk, and frozen meat. There is 
a minimum wage in Jordan for specific trades.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Expropriation is unlikely in Jordan. Property receives adequate protection from legal institutions 
and the police force.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Jordan's regulatory environment is moderately bureaucratic and poses some burdens to 
business. For example, under Jordan's 1993 disabilities law, many businesses are being 
forced to retrofit their buildings to accommodate the hearing, sight, and physically disabled. 
This expense is proving to be a substantial burden on many businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Because levels of trade protectionism are so high, smuggling is a big business in Jordan.  In 
particular, computer software and related items provide significant business to black 
marketeers.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.90</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 2  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Based on the most recent available IMF statistics. The percent represents central government 
expenditure as a percentage of GDP, based on 1991 figures.

</FONT>

