<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Republic of Korea (South Korea)</TITLE>
<H2>REPUBLIC OF KOREA (SOUTH KOREA)</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Following the Korean War, economic liberalization became the standard in the South_the Republic 
of Korea_while nationalization and collectivization was the norm in communist North Korea. Cut off from 
foreign assistance in the 1960s, South Korea reformed its economy to attract foreign investment and to 
develop its export industries. With little foreign aid, Korea has become one of the fastest-growing countries 
in the world.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Korea's average tariff rate is 7.9 percent.  However, the Republic of Korea has significant non-tariff 
barriers. These include business licensing requirements and the use of anti-dumping and other duties 
which increase the cost of imports, making them less competitive with domestically manufactured 
goods.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score -  Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
South Korea has an average income tax rate of 48 percent. The 1993 tax rate applying to the average 
income level is 10 percent.  The ROK has a top corporate income tax rate of 32 percent. It also has 
a 25 percent capital gains tax and a 10 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Korea's government consumption as percentage of GDP figure is 8.8 percent, up from 3 percent in 
1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Korea's average inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 5.6 percent. Inflation increased to 6.2 percent in 
1992 and 6.5 percent in 1993. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
The government of South Korea has relied on foreign investment to build its export economy.  Foreign 
investments have been particularly useful in developing the ROK's high-tech industries, which are 
heavily involved in exports. Yet Korea's foreign investment code is subject to variable interpretation 
and is not always applied systematically. For example, foreign investors do not always receive equal 
treatment with domestic firms. Foreign investors may face discriminatory lending practices from 
local financial institutions. Some restrictions remain on land ownership.   
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Foreign banks were welcome in South Korea as early as 1967. By the early 1990s, the government had 
completely removed itself from direct ownership of banks. Local banks are permitted to underwrite, 
deal, and broker all kinds of securities and to invest in some real estate ventures.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most prices are set by the market. However, price controls are imposed on beef, electric power, garlic, 
petroleum products, red pepper, rice, and transportation services. The government also maintains 
stockpiles of foodstuffs that it releases into the market to raise or lower prices. Korea maintains a 
minimum wage law, but some companies are exempt. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property is secure in South Korea. Expropriation is very unlikely. The ROK has a stable, 
efficient legal system to protect private property.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Obtaining a business license in South Korea is a simple process. All businesses must be registered, but 
Korea's efficient process is not a major burden. However, in some cases, the government fails to 
publish all of its regulations and enforcement of some regulations remains haphazard.  Sometimes 
businesses find themselves in violation of regulations that they do not know exist. In addition, Korea 
enforces most labor standards only on domestic firms, leaving foreign firms vulnerable to radical 
labor activities like arbitrary strikes. In some cases, these activities have forced the bankruptcy of 
foreign firms, which flee the country without paying their employees. As a result, Korea mandates 
that foreign firms deposit three months worth of wages in a special account. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Korea has a fairly small black market. However, a sizable number of employers try to avoid the 
minimum wage laws.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.15</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 2  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
