<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Madagascar</TITLE>
<H2>MADAGASCAR<P></H2>
<HR SIZE=2>


<P>	Madagascar, situated off the east coast of Africa, is the world's fourth-largest island. It has 
a largely agrarian economy with rice as its largest crop. Much of its agricultural industry is state-
owned, with some large plots of land held in private hands. Gaining independence from France in 
1960, Madagascar had little economic growth in the 1960s. In 1970 its economy took a massive 
turn for the worse because the government moved from a market-based economy to a command 
economy.  However, beginning in 1988, the government began to institute some limited economic 
reforms that have produced modest rates of economic growth. In 1991, calls for political reforms 
sidetracked economic reforms. Today, Madagascar's economy is in shambles as economic reforms 
have stalled. 
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Madagascar has an average tariff rate of 23.7 percent. It maintains other barriers by using 
consumption taxes and other import taxes which significantly increase the price of imports.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Madagascar has a top income tax rate of 35 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   
Madagascar has a top corporate income tax of 35 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
The government of Madagascar consumes 15.1 percent of GDP. It has a large state-owned 
sector.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Madagascar had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 16.8 percent. It fell to 
12.2 percent in 1992. In 1993, inflation was about 11 percent.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
All foreign investors must apply to the Ministry of Finance. Foreign investors are not treated as 
well  as domestic investors. In fact, investment restrictions exist on foreign investments in 
banking and insurance, energy, water, hydrocarbon production, mining, and petroleum 
industries.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Private banking is now allowed in some limited instances and limited foreign investment is 
permitted. Still, the banking system remains under strict control of the government, 
particularly in such areas as setting interest rates.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most prices have been freed from government control, but some price controls still exist on 
certain products. Madagascar has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property expropriation remains likely. Private property receives little legal protection.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Madagascar's economy remains moderately regulated by the government. Few private 
businesses are free from government health and safety requirements. However, the 
regulations are applied uniformly
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Madagascar has a large black market.  Even staple products such as foodstuffs are sold on the 
black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.50</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  It was not possible to determine the tax on the average income level. Therefore, Madagascar was 
scored based on its top income tax rate.

</FONT>

