<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Malawi</TITLE>
<H2>MALAWI</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Malawi is located in central Africa. It gained independence from Britain in 1964. 
Throughout the rest of the 1960s and into the 1970s, Malawi used increased agricultural production 
as an engine for economic growth. During that period, Malawi's GDP more than doubled with 3 
percent annual growth rates.  However, this changed in the 1980s. As drought brought on an 
agricultural depression, and as refugees from the nearby Mozambique civil war flowed into the 
country, Malawi's economy sank into a deep recession.  The government responded by restricting 
imports and raising government spending on social programs. This caused the budget deficit to 
balloon and pushed the country further into a depression.  As a result, Malawi's economy shrank 
nearly 8 percent and real per capita GDP dropped by 11 percent in 1992. The government has yet 
to recover from the depression.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Malawi has an average tariff rate of 10.5 percent. It imposes non-tariff barriers like strict import 
licenses on imports of eggs and poultry. In addition, Malawi maintains a government-owned 
trading company, the Import and Export Company of Malawi, which can import items 
duty-free. This hinders private sector importers who have to compete with duty-free 
imports.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR> 
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Malawi has a top income tax rate of 40 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   Malawi's 
top corporate tax rate is 35 percent. Malawi also maintains municipal taxes, a border tax, 
and a capital gains tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Malawi's government consumption as a percent of GDP is 18.6 percent. In addition, Malawi 
has a large public sector. Specifically, it operates marketing boards for some agricultural 
products. These marketing boards allow the government to confiscate crops from farmers, 
pay lower than market value prices, and export them at higher prices, keeping the profits.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Malawi had an average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 14.9 percent. This 
increased to 15.3 percent in 1992. No reliable figures are available yet for 1993 or 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
The government encourages foreign investment only in industries that produce goods for 
export. Thus, the government does not restrict foreign investments in the coffee, sugar, or 
tea industries.  However, it does restrict foreign investments in the production of consumer 
goods for the domestic market.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Of the five major banks in Malawi, only one is totally free from government ownership. 
Although the government completely freed interest rates in 1992, it still exercises a great 
deal of control over the country's financial system. Corruption is rare. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls have been lifted on almost all products, but they still remain on some food items 
and energy. Malawi maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Malawi has begun a huge privatization program aimed at selling its biggest state-owned 
enterprises. Nevertheless, despite plans to eliminate them, marketing boards still control the 
sale of agricultural products such as corn and fertilizer. The enforcement of laws protecting 
private property is lax.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
The government heavily regulates the sale of such agricultural products such as corn and 
fertilizer. Health and safety regulations are enforced erratically, causing confusion among 
businesses.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score:  4-Stable (High level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The government strictly controls the importation of food. Thus, there is a huge black market in 
such items as eggs and poultry, which often are imported illegally.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.40</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  It was not possible to determine the tax on the average income level. Therefore, Malawi was 
graded solely on its top income tax rate.
</FONT>

