<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Malaysia</TITLE>
<H2>MALAYSIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Southeast Asian country of Malaysia gained its independence from the Britain in 1957. 
In 1963, Singapore, Sarawak, and Sabah (North Borneo) joined the Federation of Malaya to form 
Malaysia. Singapore, however, withdrew in 1964 to become an independent nation. Since then 
Malaysia has undergone civil unrest and political instability. However, economic reforms began in 
the 1970s, and today Malaysia has made great progress in developing a free market.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Malaysia has an average tariff rate of 9 percent. Non-tariff barriers exist through the use of 
import bans, licensing requirements, and strict labeling requirements.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR> 
Total Taxation Score: 2.5 (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Malaysia has a top income tax rate of 34 percent. The rate that applies to the average income 
level is zero percent. Malaysia has a top corporate tax of 32 percent. This level will be 
reduced to 30 percent in 1995.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2+ (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Malaysia has a government consumption of GDP figure of 13.5 percent.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Malaysia had an average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 1.7 percent. This has 
increased to about 4 percent today.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Malaysia is relatively open to foreign investment. Most restrictions are on investments in utilities 
and those industries considered essential to national security. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Malaysia's banking industry is under moderate control of the government. Competition is 
limited by government restrictions on banks which prevent them from providing all types of 
financial services.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most wages and prices are determined by the market. Malaysia has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Chances of property expropriation remain small. However, protection of private property by the 
courts is sometimes incomplete.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Malaysia has eliminated most regulations that posed significant burdens on business. Its 
regulatory regime is efficient and relatively free of corruption.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Malaysia has a minimal black market. Most services are supplied legally, and there exists little 
incentive to engage in the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.15</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 3  
Taxation 2.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

