<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Mali</TITLE>
<H2>MALI</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	A vast and sparsely populated West African country, Mali is one of the world's poorest 
countries. It received its independence from France in 1960. Immediately thereafter, it adopted 
socialist economic policies under the leadership of President Modibo Keita. After years of a state-
dominated economic policy, Mali has begun to rely more on the market for everyday economic 
decisions. In 1992, it held its first democratic national elections, which were contested by 21 
political parties and judged to be free and fair.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Mali has an average tariff rate of about 10 percent. However, Mali uses a complex system of 
"fiscal duties" which range from 5 percent to 30 percent. Some imported goods like 
automobiles receive additional taxes of up to 100 percent.<FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>  
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR> 
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Mali has a top income and corporate tax rate of over 50 percent.<FONT SIZE="-
2">[2]</FONT>  It also has a capital gains tax and a turnover tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Mali's total government expenditure as percentage of GDP was 26.6 percent for 1990-
1991.<FONT SIZE="-2">[3]</FONT>  Mali's public sector is huge.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Mali's average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 4.4 percent. Inflation fell to 2.4 
percent in 1992. No reliable figures are available for later years.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
The government has an established investment code and investments are allowed in most areas. 
Foreign businesses are treated equally under the law with domestic businesses.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The biggest impediments to banking in Mali are corrupt government bureaucrats, collusion by 
some banks to maintain high interest rates, and a generally chaotic financial system.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most price controls have been removed. However, the government's large public sector 
influences prices. Mali has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is at risk because of high crime rates, government expropriation, and an inefficient 
court system.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Regulations are applied sporadically, and government corruption increases the risk of doing 
business.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Mali has a large black market in smuggled consumer electronics equipment like video cassette 
recorders. Also, auto parts are stolen from operating cars, only to be resold by black 
marketeers.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.50</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 4  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Mali's average tariff rate does not include fiscal duties, which increase it to between 10 percent 
and 15 percent.<BR>
[2]  According to the State Department, Mali's total taxation on income and on corporate profits is over 
50 percent. It was not possible to obtain the tax rate on the average income level. Therefore, Mali was 
scored based only on the top rate.<BR>
[3]  Total government expenditure as a percentage of GDP was used here because reliable government 
consumption figures are not available. From Adjustment in Africa, A World Bank Policy Research 
Report, The World Bank, Washington, D.C., 1994.

</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
