<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Malta</TITLE>
<H2>MALTA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Located in the Mediterranean Sea, the island nation of Malta gained its independence from 
Britain in 1964. During the 1970s, Malta's socialist experiments left many businesses bankrupt. 
Instead of letting the businesses fail, the government nationalized them. This caused the budget to 
become bloated. Today, Malta has made progress toward free market reform. It has reduced some 
taxes, maintained a tight money supply, and welcomed most foreign investment.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Malta has an average tariff rate of 10.7 percent. Some import licenses are required, especially 
for health and environmental products. 
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Malta has a top marginal income tax rate of 35 percent. Citizens making the average income 
pay a tax of 23 percent. Malta's top corporate tax rate is 35 percent. Malta has a 35 percent 
capital gains tax and a stamp duty, which is a tax on the transfer of property, of 2 percent 
to 7 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Malta's government consumes 44.4 percent of GDP.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Malta had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of  2.1 percent. The rate has 
remained rather constant since then, running at about 2 percent.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
With the exception of utilities, almost all companies are open to foreign investment. There are 
few restrictions. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Most domestic banks are controlled by the government. Still, there is competition among these 
banks to attract customers. Foreign banks are largely absent. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Malta's Department of Trade is responsible for pricing most items sold in Malta. There also is a 
minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property expropriation in Malta is possible. The court system is relatively weak in enforcing 
property rights laws.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
There are no consumer safety regulations in Malta, although the government has plans to 
introduce them. Environmental regulations are stringently enforced, and they carry large 
fines. Opening a business in Malta is difficult, and licenses must be granted by many 
institutions, including the police.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Malta is a large center for smuggling. Its location makes it a preferred base for those engaged in 
black market activity.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.25</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 4  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This figure is based on central government expenditures as a percentage of GDP. From 
<I>Government Financial Statistics Yearbook</I>: 1993, International Monetary Fund, Washington, 
D.C., 1993.

</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
