<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Mongolia</TITLE>
<H2>MONGOLIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	In Central Asia between Russia and China, Mongolia became an independent state in 1921. 
However, its economy remained closely linked with that of the Soviet Union, and it copied the 
Soviet model of central economic planning. After the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, 
Mongolia embarked on an economic liberalization program. While much remains to be done, 
Mongolia has made significant progress.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Mongolia has an average tariff rate of 15 percent. Mongolia's archaic customs procedures pose 
significant non-tariff barriers to international trade. Imports can sit at the border for lengthy 
periods before being approved for entry into the country.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: N/A<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: N/A<BR>
Total Taxation Score: N/A</I><BR>

<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Mongolia's government consumes 32.9 percent of GDP. A significant portion of the economy 
is state-owned.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Mongolia had an annual inflation rate of 195 percent in 1992.<FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>   It was about 300 percent in 1993.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Mongolia recently passed legislation to protect private property and foreign investments from 
government expropriation. New laws also provide equal treatment for Mongolian and 
foreign companies. Restrictions on currencies and profits have also been removed. 
However, potential foreign investors still must comply with cumbersome documentation 
requirements that hinder investments. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Although some progress has been made in deregulating Mongolia's banks, they still remain 
under government control. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Mongolia controls prices through a complex system of government procurement. For example, 
the government often will buy a significant amount of a particular product so it can control 
the supply, thus affecting the price. However, there has been notable progress in liberalizing 
prices as the government has allowed the market to play a more prominent role. Mongolia 
has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property expropriation is very unlikely. The government has just instituted new laws to protect 
property owners. Enforcement of laws protecting private property, however, is not as 
strong as it could be.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>   
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
The growing private sector in Mongolia, especially newly privatized companies, is still under a 
significant amount of control by the government. While few official regulations yet exist, 
corruption and government meddling in the private sector prove to be a burden to the 
operation of private business.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The government buys many goods through its complex procurement program. This distorts 
prices for food commodities. The result is a black market in these and other goods which 
are regulated by the government.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.33</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation N/A			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This figure is based on the most recent available data.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
