<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Morocco</TITLE>
<H2>MOROCCO</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The North African country of Morocco gained its independence from France in 1956. A 
constitutional monarchy, the government of King Hassan II recently has imposed free market 
reforms on the country's mixed economy. For example, taxes, tariffs, government spending, and 
subsidies have been reduced. The Moroccan economy has experienced slow but steady growth in 
recent years, and it aspires to become a major manufacturing base, serving markets in both Europe 
and Africa. However, Morocco's expensive military effort to retain control over the disputed 
Western Sahara is potentially destabilizing to its regime.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Morocco's average tariff rate is 17.6 percent. In recent years it has moved away from such 
protectionist measures as government monopolies and import licenses to straightforward 
tariffs for all but a few goods. Value-added taxes are also levied on imported goods at rates 
of between 7 percent and 30 percent, depending on the imported product.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4+ (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 4+ (High tax rates) </I><BR>
The government plans to reduce the general income tax from 48 percent to 47 percent, 
following a previous reduction from 52 percent in 1993. However, the lowest rates will 
apply to people who previously were exempt from paying taxes.<FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>   The corporation tax rate is fixed at 36 percent of profits. This is down 
from 40 percent in 1992. A value-added tax is payable at rates of 7 percent or 19 percent 
on sales and 7 percent on banking activities. 
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
The Moroccan government's consumption as percentage of GDP is 15.3 percent. Morocco's 
ambitious privatization effort began in 1992. Over 100 government-owned enterprises 
worth over $2 billion are slated to be sold by 1995. King Hassan exercises governmental 
control over several major Moroccan commercial enterprises.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Morocco's average annual rate of inflation was 7.1 percent between 1980 and 1991. It was 4.5 
percent for 1993. 
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Foreign and locally owned investments are treated the same by the government. One hundred 
percent foreign ownership is permitted. Tax holidays are granted, and there is a tax-free 
zone at Tangier. However, neither foreigners nor Moroccans may invest in industries 
competing with the state energy and water monopoly, rail and transportation services, or 
the mining and processing of phosphates.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Foreign banks are relatively free to operate in Morocco. They are permitted to possess 
controlling interests in Moroccan banks. However, the government is heavily involved in 
banking. For example, the government controls credit through government-owned financial 
institutions.  Moreover, over 20 insurance companies are subject to regulations concerning 
the investment of their funds in certain sectors of the economy. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls recently have been eliminated except on bread, cereal, gasoline, milk, and sugar. 
These products also are subsidized by the state. While wage and salary increases are freely 
negotiated between the government and businesses, there is a minimum wage. When the 
Central Commission for Prices and Wages records an increase of at least 5 percent in the 
cost of living, the government can raise all wages and prices by decree.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
The Moroccan constitution prohibits the expropriation of private property except in special 
cases prescribed by law. There are no outstanding cases of expropriation or nationalization 
of investments. However, disparities in wealth continue to breed class resentment against 
property owners. 
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
While there are no significant bureaucratic obstacles to business activities, the large bureaucracy 
presents problems, particularly for foreign investors. Foreign businesses face complicated 
procedures, special taxes, and corruption. There also are cumbersome administrative 
procedures which local banks must follow. 
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The black market is estimated to be 20 percent of GDP.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.90</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Morocco's income tax score is based solely on its maximum bracket.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
