<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Poland</TITLE>
<H2>POLAND</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Once a communist member of the Soviet-dominated Warsaw Pact, Poland has made 
economic progress since the fall of the Iron Curtain. Poland's six-party coalition, led by Prime 
Minister Hanna Suchocka, collapsed in September 1993. It was replaced in 1994 by a two-party 
alliance of the former Communist Party and the Agrarian Party. While the new government says 
that it wants to continue economic reform, it faces increasing populist pressures from disillusioned 
constituents. Farmers want more agricultural subsidies, while other groups want export subsidies 
and more welfare spending for the poor.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Poland has an average tariff rate of 14 percent.  Non-tariff barriers include strict product 
standards and labeling requirements.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Poland has a top income tax rate of 45 percent, up from 40 percent in 1993. However, the 
average income level is taxed at a rate of zero percent. Poland has a top corporate tax rate 
of 40 percent. In addition, Poland has a 40 percent capital gains tax and a 22 percent value 
added tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Poland's government consumes around 20 percent of GDP.  However, more than 50 percent 
of industrial production is generated by the state-owned sector of the economy.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5- (Very high levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Poland's annual inflation rate between 1980 and 1991 was 63.1 percent. It went down to 41 
percent in 1992. 
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Domestic and foreign firms are treated equally under the investment laws. While Poland has 
freed some regulations on foreign investment, there is a considerable amount of uncertainty 
and unpredictability which can deter foreign investors.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The banking system, although becoming more private, is still controlled by the government. 
Interest rates are not always set by market standards and may be driven by government 
budgetary concerns. This makes it harder for Poland's banks to provide affordable credit to 
needy businesses. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Firms must gain permission from the government to raise prices on certain products. This is 
true for fuel, transportation, and rent. Permission to raise prices may take as long as three 
months. Poland has a minimum wage law. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
While private property is a constitutional right in Poland, it is not adequately protected due to an 
underdeveloped court and legal system. Expropriation is possible because poor economic 
conditions could pressure the government to nationalize industry.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Despite some efforts at liberalization, Poland's regulatory regime remains an obstacle to the 
creation of new businesses. For example, some corruption still exists, and labor, health, and 
safety regulations are applied randomly. This creates uncertainty for businesses.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Poland still has a rather significant black market. Labor, transportation, construction, and other 
services are routinely supplied on the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.25</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
