<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Sierra Leone</TITLE>
<H2>SIERRA LEONE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The West African country of Sierra Leone gained independence from France in 1961. Its 
economy grew 4 percent annually during the first ten years after independence. This growth came 
to an end during the 1970s when the country's economy was devastated by the oil crisis. Over the 
past fifteen years the government has made half-hearted efforts to reform the economy, but 
recovery has remained elusive.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Sierra Leone has an average tariff rate of about 20 percent. Non-tariff barriers exist in the form 
of excessive red tape.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Sierra Leone has a top income tax rate of 50 percent. The tax rate on the average income is 5 
percent. The corporate income tax rate is a flat 47.2 percent. Sierra Leone also has 
property taxes and a goods and services tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Sierra Leone's government consumes 9.6 percent of GDP. A large state-owned sector produces 
more than 30 percent of GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5- (Very high levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Sierra Leone had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 59.3 percent. In 1992, 
it reached 95 percent. No reliable figures exist for later dates.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
All investments must be approved by the government. Foreigners are not permitted to engage in 
"local industries" like cement block manufacturing or granite and sandstone excavation. 
The manufacture of certain consumer durable goods also is closed to foreigners.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks are heavily regulated. The government sets interest rates for commercial banks. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Some price controls exist on certain foodstuffs. The government does not maintain a minimum 
wage. Prices are also influenced by the state-owned industries, which are subsidized by the 
government.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Although private property is permitted, it can be expropriated. An inefficient legal and law 
enforcement environment provides little protection. 
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Regulations are applied haphazardly, making it difficult for businesses to comply. For example, 
health and safety standards are not enforced uniformly. At other times they are, creating an 
environment of uncertainty among businesses. Nevertheless, bribes are not necessary. 
Regulations thus pose only a moderate burden on business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Sierra Leone's large tariffs have encouraged smugglers to sell many products on the black 
market. Some products like coffee and rice are sold at much lower prices than in state-
owned stores. Sierra Leone's black market activity is near the level of its legal activity.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.80</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
