<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Singapore</TITLE>
<H2>SINGAPORE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Singapore won its independence from Malaysia on August 9, 1965. Since then, the country 
has undergone economic liberalization, eventually moving the country into the industrialized world.  
Singapore had average annual growth rates of about 6.5 percent from 1965 to 1990. Today, 
Singapore is one of the richest countries in Asia.  It has made remarkable progress by maintaining 
an open trade and investment environment; a corruption-free, pro-business regulatory system; 
political stability; an efficient, strike-free labor force; and tax incentives for foreign investors.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Singapore's average tariff rate is nearly nonexistent, from 0.3 to 0.5 percent. It maintains 
straightforward labeling requirements, no import quotas, and no non-tariff barriers to 
foreign trade. Import licenses are not required, and customs procedures are minimal. The 
code regulating product standards is not an impediment to trade.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR> 
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 2.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Singapore's top rate is 30 percent. However, average income is not taxed. In fact, one needs to 
make twice the average income before the lowest taxable bracket, 21 percent, applies. 
There are no taxes on capital gains. Singapore has a flat corporate tax rate of 27 percent. It 
has a minimal value-added tax of 3 percent, which was introduced in April 1994.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Singapore's government consumption rate as percentage of GDP is 9.8 percent.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Singapore had an average annual rate of inflation of 1.9 percent from 1980 to 1991. In 1994, 
inflation is running at 3.6 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Investment laws in Singapore are clear and fair and pose few problems for businesses. Foreign 
and domestic businesses are treated equally under the investment laws. There are no 
production or local content requirements.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Foreign banks are restricted in the number of branches and automatic teller machines they may 
operate. However, all banks can participate in securities exchanges, selling insurance 
policies, and some real estate ventures. They also may invest in industrial firms. It is easy 
to form new banks.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Almost all wages and prices are set by the free market. There is no minimum wage. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Singapore has an extensive history of private property protection. There is no threat of 
expropriation. The court system is highly efficient and strongly protects private property.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Obtaining a business license in Singapore is easy. Government regulations are straightforward 
and there is very little corruption. Occupational and health regulations exist, but they are no 
burden to business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The black market in Singapore is very small.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 1.25</TH>  
    
Trade 1				Banking 2  
Taxation 2.5			Wage and Prices 1  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 1  
Foreign Investment 1		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
