<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>The Slovak Republic</TITLE>
<H2>THE SLOVAK REPUBLIC</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Slovakia's split with the Czech Republic in 1993 left much of its banking, experienced 
personnel, data analysis capabilities, and competitive industries across the border. Along with 
struggling to reform its centrally controlled economy to a market-based one, the Slovak Republic 
has agonized over creating a stable government. Reform has been slower in Slovakia than in the 
Czech Republic.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Slovakia has an average tariff rate of about 5 percent and some non-tariff barriers.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Slovakia has a top marginal income tax of 47 percent. The average taxpayer pays at a rate 
around 20 percent. Slovakia has a top corporate income tax rate of 45 percent. It also has a 
40 percent capital gains tax, a 25 percent value-added tax, and a 50 percent social 
contributions tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Slovakia's government consumes 26 percent of GDP. Yet most of the economic output is 
produced by state-owned firms.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of inflation) </I><BR>
The Slovak Republic has not been an independent country long enough to get an average 
inflation rate from 1980 to 1991. Therefore, it was graded on its average inflation rate from 
1992 to 1994, which was 17.5 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Foreign citizens may not own land in Slovakia. Few restrictions on foreign direct investment 
remain. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Permission from the central bank is required to open banks. Domestic banks are subjected to a 
moderate level of regulation and control. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls exist on food, electricity, and other items. The Slovak Republic has a minimum 
wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Expropriation is unlikely in Slovakia.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Regulations have been reduced in the Slovak Republic. Most businesses do not require a 
license. The government is reviewing its regulatory framework to further reduce any 
burdens on business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The black market remains fairly large in the Slovak Republic.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.75</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 3  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
