<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>South Africa </TITLE>
<H2>SOUTH AFRICA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	South Africa's transition from apartheid to a non-racial democracy has gone well. A key to 
the country's future stability will be the revival of a long-depressed economy. South Africa enjoys 
many economic benefits, including a modern industrial sector, a well-developed infrastructure, and 
abundant natural resources. The government over the years has maintained a great deal of control 
over the economy, and this policy is continued by the new government. However, some badly 
needed economic liberalization has begun, including the privatization of some state assets, the 
state's withdrawal from the distribution of agricultural goods, and the trimming of public sector 
personnel.  This course of liberalization is nonetheless uncertain. The new government will be 
tempted to spend more on social programs to improve quickly the lives of previously 
disenfranchised black South Africans. 
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
For many years South Africa has maintained high tariffs and other import restrictions. As a 
result, South Africa's average tariff level is a high 21 percent. South Africa's most heavily 
protected industries are textiles and motor vehicles. The average tariff on textiles and 
clothing is 100 percent.  The tariff on motor vehicles is 115 percent. The agricultural sector 
is heavily protected with tariffs, taxes, surcharges, and quotas.      
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>  
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4 (High tax rates) </I><BR>
South Africa has a progressive tax system with the highest tax bracket being 43 percent.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  The corporate tax is 40 percent. It also has a value-added 
tax of 14 percent, a financial services tax, and regional taxes.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
The South African government's consumption as percentage of GDP is 21.2 percent. Six state-
owned companies rank among the 25 largest South African firms. State assets include the 
country's railways, national airline, broadcasting services, and electric utilities
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate levels of inflation) </I><BR>
South Africa's average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 14.4 percent.  The 
current inflation rate is approximately 10 percent. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
There is no government approval required for foreign investment. Foreign investors are subject 
to the same laws as domestic investors. There are no requirements for South African 
participation in management. However, the new government led by the African National 
Congress may not maintain a hospitable investment climate. Its egalitarianism could lead to 
increased economic control by the government, which would deter investors. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Quantitative and administrative controls over deposit and lending rates have largely disappeared. 
The banking and insurance industries nevertheless are strictly controlled. Legal restrictions 
which discriminate against foreign-owned financial institutions have been eliminated.  
However, the new government may pressure the banks into making politically motivated 
loans.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
The government has abolished price controls on all but a few politically sensitive items, such as 
the supply of gas, coal, and electricity. It has also deregulated the agricultural sector. Only a 
few years ago, as many as 22 now-abolished marketing boards fixed prices for agricultural 
products. Moreover, to lower prices, the government has abolished import restrictions on 
fertilizer, farming equipment, and cement. No national minimum wage exists.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
No private-sector company, whether South African or foreign-controlled, has ever been 
nationalized. However, there is a danger that the redistributionist policies of the ANC 
government, including its land reform program, may weaken private property rights.     
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Regulation of economic activity is minimal in South Africa. It takes only takes 4 to 10 days to 
incorporate a business, and most businesses can be started with a minimum of formalities. 
While licenses are required for certain activities, they can be obtained with relative ease. 
However, there will be increasing political pressure to practice more affirmative action in 
the hiring and firing of personnel.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Legal restrictions which prevented black South Africans from owning businesses, obtaining 
skilled jobs, or living in major urban centers were lifted in 1991. This will reduce black 
market activity. Nevertheless, South Africa's continued high level of trade restrictions 
encourages smuggling.   
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.00</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  South Africa's income tax score is based solely on its maximum bracket.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
