<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Spain</TITLE>
<H2>SPAIN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Spain's economy has long been dominated by the state. As a result, it lags behind most of 
its European neighbors. Yet Spain's accession into the European Union in 1986 has forced the 
government to open its economy, remove oppressive government-run bureaucracies from many 
economic decisions, and expand the free market. After several years of economic growth that began 
in 1986, Spain entered a deep recession in 1992 that for the most part continues until this day. This 
recession was mainly the result of renewed government intervention in the economy.  Despite some 
progress on reform, the socialist government of Felipe Gonzalez has yet to choose a clear and 
consistent path of free market reforms.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Spain has an average tariff rate of about 3.6 percent. However, it imposes non-tariff barriers in 
the form of restrictive customs procedures, strict labeling and testing requirements, and a 
host of other barriers.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Spain has a top income tax rate of 56 percent. The tax on the average income level is 24.5 
percent. The top corporate rate is 35 percent. Spain has a 35 percent capital gains tax and a 
15 percent value-added tax. 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Spain's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 16 percent. However, state 
ownership of industry remains extensive.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Spain had an average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of  8.9 percent. This fell to 6.1 
percent in 1992 and 4.5 percent in 1993. Inflation was about 4 percent in 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Spain's membership in the European Union has forced Madrid to remove most restrictions on 
foreign investment. Few restrictions remain.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Spain's banking system has become more competitive since its integration into the European 
Union. It has been forced to accept banks from other EU countries, but they face 
cumbersome regulations.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls exist on the supply of electricity and pharmaceutical products. Spain maintains a 
minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is safe from government expropriation. Spain's legal system effectively protects 
private property, although levels of corruption are higher than in most other EU countries.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Spain's government maintains many regulations on businesses. These include labor and 
environmental laws, plus regulations dealing with fringe benefits. These pose a moderate 
burden for businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Because of price controls, Spain has a black market in pharmaceutical products. Otherwise 
there is not much of a black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.60</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 2  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
