<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Sri Lanka</TITLE>
<H2>SRI LANKA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Sri Lanka, an island off the southern shore of India, declared its independence from Britain 
in 1972. Since then the country has struggled with civil unrest and, most recently, civil war. This 
war is a drain on the economy. Even though the war continues, the government launched a far-
reaching economic restructuring plan in 1988 that has propelled Sri Lanka into substantial growth 
rates. The government has focused on reducing trade barriers, privatizing businesses, and expanding 
the role of the private sector.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka has an average tariff rate of 15.4 percent. It has non-tariff barriers in many areas. A 
Special Import License, for example, is needed to import pharmaceutical products, textiles, 
and automobiles. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I> <BR>
Sri Lanka has a top marginal income tax rate of 35 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  
Sri Lanka has a top corporate income tax rate of 45 percent. It also has a 1 percent to 20 
percent turnover tax and a social contributions tax.   
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 9.3 percent, up from 8.5 percent 
in 1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka had an average annual inflation rate between 1980 and 1991 of 10.1 percent. 
Inflation was 11.4 percent in 1992 and around 12 percent in 1993.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka does not permit foreign investment in education, the harvest and sale of coconuts, 
and the deep sea fishing, mining, shipping, telecommunications, timber, transportation, and 
travel indus-tries. In addition, the government imposes severe limits on foreign investment 
in the banking, finance, insurance, and securities industries. There is though, an established 
investment code.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka has over 20 commercial banks, most of which are foreign-owned. There are both 
private and state-owned banks. Competition in the Sri Lankan banking sector has made the 
industry increasingly more efficient. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most wages and prices are determined by the market. Some controls, however, exist on such 
items as foodstuffs and some energy products. Sri Lanka does not have a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka has an efficient and functional court system. However, expropriation remain possible 
because current economic conditions may pressure the government to nationalize 
businesses.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka has an efficient and stable bureaucracy. Because of corruption, however, regulations 
can pose a moderate burden to businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4- (High level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Sri Lanka has a large black market. The civil war has created conditions in which smuggling is 
widespread.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.80</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 2  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 1  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  It was not possible to determine the average income tax rate. As a result, Sri Lanka was graded 
only on the top marginal tax rate.

</FONT>
<BR>
