<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Sudan </TITLE>
<H2>SUDAN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The sub-Saharan African country of Sudan gained independence from the Britain in 1956. 
It is Africa's largest country. President Omar Hassan al-Bashir's Islamic fundamentalist regime, 
which seized power in a 1989 coup, is authoritarian and increasingly isolated internationally. Sudan 
was declared a supporter of terrorism by the U.S. State Department in 1993. The ruling National 
Islamic Front tolerates no political opposition and is engaged in an expensive and brutal civil war 
with southern Sudanese separatists. Though the government has implemented modest economic 
liberalizations, Sudan's economy is unfree and continues to deteriorate. Sudan's economic 
mismanagement and its radical politics have left it with few remaining foreign aid donors.  
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Sudan's average tariff rate is 24 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   Import and export 
licenses have recently been eliminated, though the importation of some 30 items is banned. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)</I><BR>
Sudan has top income and corporate tax rates of 60 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT> 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: Not Scored</I><BR>
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
Annual inflation is running at over 100 percent. This rate is expected to increase as the 
Sudanese economy continues to decline.<FONT SIZE="-2">[3]</FONT> 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
The Islamic government is very sensitive to outside interference in its affairs. This creates an 
inhospitable foreign investment environment. Foreign investment is approved on a case-by-
case basis. Foreign investment is not permitted in wholesale or retail companies or in the 
production of  cotton. Bureaucratic procedures designed to encourage the employment of 
domestic laborers are cumbersome.  However, there is no tax discrimination against foreign 
investment. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4- (High level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
The new regime has moved to "Islamicize" the state-controlled banking system. This has 
increased government control over economic enterprises. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Sudan has liberalized some prices, though price controls remain on foodstuffs. Many goods are 
subsidized. The government regulates public and private salaries. Sudan has a minimum 
wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
There is little respect for private property in Sudan. The judiciary is not independent. The 
wanton destruction of private property by government troops is widespread in southern 
Sudan. 
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government regulation)</I><BR>
Bureaucratic inefficiency makes business activity difficult. As with many developing countries, 
however, the regulatory burden is light. The government has cracked down on corruption, 
although it remains a problem.    
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Rationing has led to a black market for several items, including petroleum and sugar. The ban 
on some imports encourages smuggling. The U.S. State Department reports that a slave 
trade exists in Sudan. 
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 4.22</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 4  
Government Consumption N/A 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]   This figure is for 1992/93 and includes a defense tax. Source: United States Department of 
State, Bureau of African Affairs, Office of Economic Policy.<BR>
[2]  The most recent reliable information is based on 1989 tax data from World Bank sources. There is 
insufficient information to determine the tax rate on the average income level; thus, Sudan was graded on 
its top tax rate.<BR>
[3]  Sudan's monetary policy score is based on its current inflation rate, not its historical annual inflation 
rate, which is unavailable.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
