<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Sweden</TITLE>
<H2>SWEDEN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Sweden's economy has changed dramatically over the last several years. Once considered a 
workable socialist economy, Sweden experienced a severe economic recession in the 1980s that 
exploded the myth that a cradle-to-grave welfare state could be maintained without destroying the 
economy. By the end of the 1980s, it became increasingly clear that Sweden's economic policies, 
which included tax rates as high as 98 percent, were leading the country down the road to economic 
ruin. Because of  Sweden's generous social welfare spending, worker retraining programs, high 
unemployment compensation, and high tax rates, Sweden's GDP shrank by 6 percent from 1991 to 
1993 and unemployment rose to around 10 percent. In the end, Sweden was forced to abandon 
most of its socialist policies and follow a more market-oriented economy. Proving to be far from a 
"worker's paradise," Sweden now stands as a shining example of how socialism, no matter how 
watered down, does not work and how real economic reform produces sustainable economic 
growth.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Sweden's average tariff rate is about 3 percent on manufactured goods and 5 percent on 
finished goods. Thus, the average rate is around 4 percent.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  However, Sweden maintains significant import licensing 
procedures for such items as agricultural goods, ferroalloys, fiberboard, and semi-finished 
iron and steel.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5+ (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable  (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
The Swedish tax burden is one of the heaviest in Europe.<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>   
The tax burden consumes about 50 percent of GDP. Sweden has a top income tax rate of 
50 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[3]</FONT>   The tax rate that applies to the average 
income level is 30 percent. Sweden's top corporate tax rate is 28 percent. It also has a 21 
percent to 25 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Sweden's government expenditures account for around 75 percent of GDP.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[4]</FONT>  Sweden, understanding its economic malaise, is attempting 
to reduce government spending. 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Sweden's average inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 7.4 percent. This rate is dropping 
because Sweden has pegged its currency to the European currency unit (ECU) and has 
followed a tighter monetary policy. Inflation rates since 1991 have averaged around 3 
percent to 4 percent per year.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Sweden has few barriers to foreign investment. However, some restrictions continue on foreign 
ownership of air transportation companies, the maritime industry, and items considered 
necessary during time of war, such as arms manufacturing.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
All commercial banks in Sweden but one are domestically owned and operated.  Two more are 
directly owned by the government. While foreign banks have been permitted to establish 
subsidiaries and branches in Sweden since 1980, the application process still remains a 
barrier for most foreign bankers. However, the government is trying to liberalize the 
banking system, making it easier to open new banks.<FONT SIZE="-2">[5]</FONT>  
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. There is no national minimum wage law. 
However, the government influences wage rates by establishing a minimum wage for 
employees of state-owned industries. Prices are also affected by government-owned 
businesses, which are subsidized.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
While Sweden has a rather extensive history of nationalization and expropriation of private 
property, it has recently undertaken a massive privatization program that is returning private 
property to the private sector. However, private property still receives less protection in 
Sweden than it does in other parts of Western Europe or in North America.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Obtaining a business license in Sweden is relatively easy.  Businesses must register with the 
Patent and Registration Office and the appropriate tax offices. Moreover, Sweden 
maintains a comprehensive safety, environmental and consumer regulatory structure that 
poses a burden to businesses.  For example, the Environmental Protection Act of 1969 
requires all businesses to obtain permission from the government before they release any 
pollutants into the environment. In cases where the expansion of a business may result in 
more pollution, a company must undergo a lengthy and sometimes extremely burdensome 
investigation.  There are many other regulations on businesses, such as a government-
imposed five-week vacation.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
While Sweden once had a rather large black market in the construction industry, economic 
reforms are making it easier for most goods and services to be exchanged legally.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.65</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 3  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Country Reports on Economic Policy and Trade Practices, p. 277.<BR>
[2]  Ibid., p. 276.<BR>
[3]  Includes a local tax rate of 30 percent.<BR>
[4] Based on central government expenditure, from <I>Country Reports on Economic Policy and Trade 
Practices</I>, p. 276.<BR>
[5] In addition to the sources noted in the "Banking Factor" section, "Banking and Finance in Sweden," 
KPMG Bohlins, Stockholm, Sweden, 1993 was used.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
