<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Uganda </TITLE>
<H2>UGANDA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Since gaining independence from Britain in 1962, the central African country of Uganda 
has suffered through years of civil strife and economic deterioration. The decline of the Ugandan 
economy, which was once one of the more promising in Africa, was accelerated by government 
control and mismanagement. Uganda's unelected president, Yoweri Museveni, rules with an iron 
hand. Nevertheless, despite the absence of political freedom, Museveni's government has liberalized 
the economy by removing the state from some sectors of the economy. The regime is now more or 
less stable, but pressures exist to democratize the regime.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
This year the highest import duty was reduced from 80 percent to 30 percent, and the lowest 
duty was reduced from 50 percent to 10 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   The 
Ministry of Commerce reserves the right to restrict the import of goods which compete 
with local industries.     
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Uganda has a top income tax rate of 30 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>   The 
corporate tax rate in Uganda is 30 percent. Uganda also has a 15 percent business turnover 
tax and a sales tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score:  2+ (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Uganda's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 7.2 percent. Although the 
Museveni government has privatized some state assets, the state sector remains large.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
The Museveni government has made significant strides in controlling Uganda's long-standing 
inflation problem. Inflation between 1980 and 1990 averaged 107 percent annually.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[3]</FONT>   Inflation is estimated at 15 percent today.  
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
The Museveni government has moved to reduce foreign investment barriers. Foreign investors 
now may fully own Ugandan companies. Foreign-owned investments are treated in a 
nondiscriminatory manner. Investment incentives exist, such as some tax holidays. 
However, foreigners may not own agricultural land.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Uganda's financial sector is small and dominated by the state. Nevertheless, a number of 
foreign banks operate in Uganda. Many non-bank financial institutions, including 21 
insurance companies, also exist. There are plans to establish a Ugandan stock exchange.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most prices are based on the market. The abolition of coffee, cotton, and other government 
monopolies allows the market to set wages and prices in these important sectors. Uganda 
does not have a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protection of property rights)</I><BR>
The government is proceeding, albeit slowly, with the privatization of state assets. It is also 
returning property that was confiscated under previous regimes. Future government 
confiscation is unlikely. However, tribal land tenure systems pose challenges to the 
establishment of a strong property rights regime. The outright ownership of land is not 
permitted. Widespread corruption also works against the protection of property.   
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: Not Scored </I><FONT SIZE="-2">[4]</FONT><BR>
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The smuggling of cigarettes is widespread in Uganda. However, the government has recently 
announced plans to step up its campaign against smuggling.  Black market activity has 
decreased as Uganda's economy has become more liberalized.   
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.94</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation N/A  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Uganda's average tariff rate was unavailable. The mentioned duty schedule, reported by the U.S. 
Department of Commerce's<I> Country Commercial Guide</I>, supports an assumption that Uganda's 
average tariff rate falls between 15 and 19 percent.<BR>
[2]   Uganda's income tax score is based solely on its maximum rate.<BR>
[3] <I> World Development Report 1992: Development and the Environment</I>, published for the 
World Bank by Oxford University Press, p. 242.<BR>
[4]  Reliable information was not available for this factor.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
