<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Ukraine</TITLE>
<H2>UKRAINE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Ukraine became an independent republic in 1991. It has been very slow to shake off its 
communist past.  The first government of Leonid Kravchuk was composed of old communist 
apparatchiks who resisted reform.  The result has been that Ukraine has made less progress than 
Russia in reforming its economy.  However, there is some hope that the new government of Leonid 
Kuchma, who was elected president in 1994, will begin to turn things around.  Kuchma has plans to 
balance the budget, reduce wasteful subsidies to state-owned industries, privatize the massive state 
sector of the economy, and reduce barriers to trade.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Ukraine has tariffs that range from 5 percent to 20 percent, with some rates being especially 
high for such goods as alcohol.  The average tariff rate is about 15 percent.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   Ukraine has domestic production standards and 
certification requirements for all products.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR> 
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Ukraine has a top income tax rate of 90 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>   Ukraine 
has a top corporate tax rate of 22 percent, an 18 percent capital gains tax, and a 28 percent 
value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Ukraine's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 18 percent. The public sector is 
still large and produces most of the GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Ukraine had an annual inflation rate of over 1,400 percent in 1992.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[3]</FONT>   That rate was reduced significantly to about 72 percent in 
1993.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Ukraine provides up to 10 years in tax holidays for huge investments in such priority areas as 
advanced technologies for agricultural production and high-tech consumer goods. There are 
no regulations on repatriation of capital or profits. Few restrictions exist on foreign 
ownership of businesses. However, the unpredictability of laws and the slow progress of 
reforms deter foreign investors.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Ukraine's banking environment remains in chaos and is under the strict control of the 
government. While the number of private banks has grown, they remain in direct 
competition with government-controlled and -subsidized banks.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Wages for jobs in the industrial sectors are controlled by the government. Some prices are still 
controlled by the government, especially in housing, transportation services, and public 
utilities. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Ukraine has yet to establish a legal system that sufficiently protects private property. Although 
the government is following an ambitious program to privatize large sectors of the 
economy, property still remains subject to government expropriation.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
The haphazard application of regulations is a significant barrier to business. There is widespread 
corruption in the bureaucracy which sometime results in steep fines on businesses for 
violations of Ukraine's regulations. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Because Ukraine's economy still is controlled by the government, much business activity is still 
performed in the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.90</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This estimate is based on information provided by the Ukrainian Embassy.<BR>
[2]  Reliable information was not available to determine the tax on the average income level. Therefore, 
Ukraine was scored on the top marginal rate.<BR>
[3]  Average inflation rate information on Ukraine is not available. Therefore, Ukraine's inflation score 
was based on the most recent available data.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
