<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>United Kingdom</TITLE>
<H2>UNITED KINGDOM</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	This constitutional monarchy has gone from periods of experimentation with socialism to 
spurts of free market capitalism. Facing near economic collapse in the 1970s, the U.K. turned to 
free market reform under the leadership of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher. The result was an 
extensive market liberalization policy that has made Britain one of the strongest economies in the 
European Union. Thatcher's reforms provide an example not only of how increased economic 
freedom produces sustained economic growth, but of how a country that was once sliding back 
down the scale of economic freedom can turn itself around.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
The U.K. has an average tariff rate of 3.6 percent. Although some progress has been made in 
opening the U.K. market to imports, some non-tariff barriers still remain in 
telecommunications and the energy industry.  
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5+ (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5+ (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
The U.K. has a top income tax rate of 40 percent. The tax on the average income level is 25 
percent. For the tax year ending March 31, 1993, the top corporate tax rate was 33 percent. 
It also has a 33 percent capital gains tax and a 17.5 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Britain's government consumes about 35 percent of GDP.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
The U.K.'s average annual inflation rate was 5.8 percent from 1980 to 1991. Inflation was 4.5 
percent in 1992; 3 percent in 1993, and 2.4 percent for most of 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Many non-European companies use Britain as a base for setting up businesses in Europe. The 
U.K. also is the largest recipient of U.S. and Japanese foreign investment in Europe. 
However, despite a generally hospitable environment for foreign investment, there are still 
some restrictions on foreign investments in the aerospace industry and public utilities.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Britain's banking system is fairly open to competition. Most credit is supplied by privately 
owned banks. However, the 1987 Banking Act gives the Bank of England the right to 
prevent the foreign ownership of more than 15 percent of any British bank. Banks are 
permitted to sell securities, insurance policies, and real estate, as well as to invest in 
industrial firms. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Prices for the most part are set by the market. However, prices charged by public utilities are 
fixed. In addition, the government controls the prices of some products and services, 
including matches, milk, and taxi fares. There are no minimum wage laws.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
The government of Prime Minister John Major has continued the privatization policies of 
Margaret Thatcher. Most of Britain's economy is private. The court system is efficient and 
provides maximum protection of private property.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of regulation) </I><BR>
It is easy to open a business in the U.K. While Britain's regulatory system imposes some 
burdens on business, it also has gone further to reduce regulations than most industrialized 
countries. The U.K., for example, has a regulatory regime that permits companies to self-
regulate their industries.  Businesses subscribe voluntarily to a code of conduct that, if 
violated, will cause them to be penalized by consumers who will see their products as 
shoddy. There are few environmental laws in Britain.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The U.K.'s black market is, like the rest of the developed world, restricted to drugs, guns, and 
other illegal activities.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 1.95</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 2  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 1  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 1 
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  For this figure, government expenditure as a percentage of GDP was calculated at market prices 
from<I> World Tables</I>, The World Bank, Washington, D.C., 1994.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
