<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Uruguay</TITLE>
<H2>URUGUAY</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Uruguay became independent from Brazil in 1828. Today, it has a relatively free and open 
market. It used to be a major international banking center until leftist economic policies introduced 
in the 1960s brought economic stagnation. It is wealthy by Latin American standards and has a 
relatively high level of literacy. The current government has been working to liberalize the economy 
and bring back respectable levels of economic growth.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Uruguay has an average tariff rate of around 11 percent. Few other restrictions remain on 
imports. Import licenses exist, but they are easy to obtain and do not restrict imports.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)  </I><BR>
There is no income tax in Uruguay. Uruguay's top corporate tax rate is 30 percent. It has a 
value-added tax of 22 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Uruguay's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 13.7 percent, up from 12.7 
percent in 1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Uruguay's average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 64.4 percent. Inflation was 
around 50 percent in 1993.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Uruguay remains relatively open to foreign investment. Among the exceptions are the so-called 
strategic industries, which include telecommunications and transportation, plus banks and 
the press. There are some tax incentives to foreign investment.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks are generally closed to foreigners. But competition between domestic banks is quite 
strong. Domestic banks are permitted to sell securities, but they are prohibited from 
involvement in insurance, real estate, and investment transactions. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Uruguay maintains a minimum wage. Most prices are determined by the market. Some price 
controls remain. This list changes often but now includes such items as dairy products and 
poultry.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Expropriation remains a possibility because the government has concerns over a growing 
separation between rich and poor. Economic inequality could create pressure on the 
government to redistribute wealth.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>   
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Establishing a business in Uruguay is a lengthy process. The bureaucracy is cumbersome and 
inefficient. Uruguay has yet to implement some of the most burdensome regulations on 
business, like strict environmental requirements, and the inefficient bureaucracy poses a 
moderate burden to businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Like most Latin American countries, Uruguay has its share of black market activity. 
Transportation and labor are two commodities often found on the black market. 
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.90</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
