<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Vietnam</TITLE>
<H2>VIETNAM</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Divided for most of its early history into warring factions, Vietnam was occupied by France 
in the 19th century.  After World War II, revolutionaries in northern Vietnam called on the French 
to withdraw. In 1954, France agreed to withdraw from the northern part of Vietnam and moved 
south below the 17th parallel. The communists in the North then established the communist 
Democratic Republic of Vietnam. Fearing economic collapse and political repression, non-
communist Vietnamese rushed south and established the Republic of South Vietnam.  After the 
defeat of South Vietnam in the Vietnam War in 1975, the communists, who now controlled the 
entire country, established a communist system for the entire country. While the government is 
liberalizing its economy in some areas, the economy remains generally repressed. 
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Vietnam suffers from a corrupt bureaucracy that creates very high barriers to imports. Many 
imports are confiscated by corrupt border officials.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Vietnam has a progressive income tax system with a top rate of 50 percent. The average 
income level is taxed at a rate of 40 percent. Taxation on foreign corporate profits is as high 
as 25 percent. However, since the economy still is essentially centrally planned and most of 
the businesses are owned by the government, the tax rates are actually much higher than 
these levels suggest.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The government still owns most of the means of production despite recent efforts to privatize. 
The government still maintains central planning and has yet to subject its economy to the 
basic principles of supply and demand.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
From 1989 to 1993, Vietnam had an annual average inflation rate of over 40 percent. For 1994, 
inflation is expected to be about 18 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Of the remaining communist states, Vietnam has gone farther to open its economy to foreign 
investment than either Cuba or North Korea. Yet much of the economy is inaccessible to 
foreigners, investments still need prior government approval, and some restrictions remain 
on repatriation of profits.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banking services in Vietnam are almost exclusively reserved for the government, although 
attempts have been made to modernize the financial system.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
At least 50 percent of the goods produced by Vietnamese companies are subject to central 
planning. Nevertheless, Vietnam has lifted price controls on some products, including steel 
and printing paper. Many wages are still set by the government.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
The government is tolerating more private ownership of property. However, there is by and 
large no legal protection of private property in Vietnam.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of regulation) </I><BR>
The Vietnamese government is reducing some regulations, but it still remains a major barrier to 
entrepreneurship and the creation of new private businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Vietnam has a large black market in the sale of such basic goods and services as foodstuffs and 
labor.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 4.70</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 4  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 5  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 5  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>


