<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Yemen</TITLE>
<H2>YEMEN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Yemen is one of the oldest regions of human habitation. After centuries of domination by 
various empires, including the Romans and the Ottomans, the southern part of Yemen became a 
protectorate of the British in 1839. Turkey controlled the northern part of Yemen. Turkey lost 
control of northern Yemen after World War I, and in 1934 it became independent. A civil war 
erupted in northern Yemen in 1962. Civil unrest spilled over into southern Yemen, forcing the 
British to withdraw in 1967. A Marxist government took over southern Yemen soon after, sending 
the economy into a nose dive. After two decades of political and civil chaos, North and South 
Yemen united into a single country in 1990.  Some progress toward economic liberalization had 
begun, but it was cut short by the outbreak of a civil war in 1994.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Yemen has an average tariff rate of about 20 percent, with tariffs ranging from 5 percent to 50 
percent. Special duties apply to some so-called luxury items, such as automobiles, which 
are assessed a 67 percent duty. Customs duties for tobacco imports are assessed at a rate 
of 145 percent. In addition, Yemen has non-tariff barriers in several areas. For example, 
import licenses are required on most items. However, the government has simplified the 
licensing procedure.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR> 
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Yemen has a top income tax rate of 28 percent. The rate that applies to the average income 
level is 9 percent. Yemen has a top corporate tax rate of 36 percent, a 32 percent capital 
gains tax, and other taxes.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Yemen's government consumes 27.9 percent of GDP.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Yemen's average annual inflation rate from 1989 to 1993 was 96.4 percent. Inflation was 
around 60 percent for 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Yemen has streamlined its investment laws and procedures in an attempt to attract more foreign 
investment. Some problems have been alleviated.  For example, Yemen has an agency 
which is a central clearing house for foreign investors. However, some barriers still exist. 
Foreigners are not permitted to invest in public utilities and in some industries like 
telecommunications. Investments are limited in other sectors as well, such as in hotels and 
restaurants.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
While the government has plans to let more foreign banks operate in Yemen, so far not much 
progress has been made. Domestic banks are still heavily regulated by the government. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Yemen's government controls some prices. This is mainly the result of the socialist legacy in 
the northern part of the country. However, Yemen has no minimum wage.   
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property has not been expropriated by the government since 1990. The threat of expropriation, 
however, still exists due to uncertain economic conditions. Moreover, terrorism is a major 
threat to private property. Auto theft is a big problem as well.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Businesses need to obtain an environmental impact study before they engage in new 
investments or expand their enterprises. Although hardly any investments have been turned 
down, the process delays some business activities. Bureaucratic inefficiencies remain a 
problem.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Because of high trade barriers, smuggling almost equals official trade. Smuggling is particularly 
bad in some scarce items such as foodstuffs.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.75</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  World Bank data, 1991.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
