</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Zambia</TITLE>
<H2>ZAMBIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Zambia gained its independence from Britain in 1964. It remained a one-party socialist state 
until 1989, when political party opposition was legalized. In 1991 Frederick Chiluba won an 
overwhelming election victory over long-time President Kenneth Kaunda. Chiluba ran on a platform 
of democracy and free enterprise. After years of disastrous economic policies, President Chiluba is 
trying to lead Zambia to economic recovery. He has liberalized the economy, pruned the civil 
service, and privatized a few state enterprises. However, he still has a long way to go.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
President Chiluba has reduced tariffs. By African standards, Zambia's average tariff rate is 
relatively low: 11.9 percent. Import restrictions have been eased. However, resentment 
against increasing South African imports is generating a new protectionist sentiment. 
Moreover, corruption in the Customs Bureau is on the rise. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3- (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5- (High tax rates) </I><BR>
In 1993 income tax rates were cut for the poor and lower middle-income groups. Zambia's top 
marginal rate is 35 percent. The average Zambian income taxpayer is in the 15 percent 
bracket. In 1993 Zambia cut its corporate tax rate to 35 percent.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  Zambia also has a 23 percent sales tax and property 
transfer taxes and plans to introduce a capital gains tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
The Zambian government consumes 10.2 percent of GDP. During the Kaunda regime, state-
owned enterprises accounted for more than 50 percent of the GDP.   
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5- (Very high levels of inflation) </I><BR>
The annual inflation rate was 67 percent in 1992.<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>   It is 
estimated at 70 percent for 1993 and 95 percent for 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
The government has improved its foreign investment laws. There is no legal discrimination 
between foreign and domestic investors, and few investment opportunities are off limits. 
Zambia is attracting commercial farmers from South Africa and Zimbabwe who fear the 
confiscation of their land. Foreign investment must be screened by an investment board, 
but it operates quickly and efficiently.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Private international and domestic banks operate in Zambia. Interest rates for loans and 
deposits are set by the market. Merchant banking has recently been legalized. However, 
Zambia still has a few state-owned banks.     
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
State subsidization of government-owned enterprises distorts the pricing system in Zambia. 
There is a minimum wage. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Kaunda's socialist regime left a legacy of nationalized property. Businesses were expropriated 
as recently as 1989. However, legislation enacted in 1993 provides for full compensation 
for newly nationalized property in convertible currency. While the government has sold 
some state enterprises, privatization is proceeding slowly. Though the courts in Zambia are 
reasonably independent, property rights protection remains weak. 
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
There are complex procedures and delays for acquiring business licenses. An investment board 
screens domestic investment. Corruption is an increasing problem. Burdensome and 
expensive labor laws exist. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Zambia's history of price controls and inefficient government monopolies has bred a huge black 
market, particularly in the agricultural sector. There is widespread evasion of taxation and 
expensive labor laws. An illicit drug trade exists in Zambia.   
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.05</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 2  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Banking profits in excess of ZK1000 million are taxed at 45 percent. This one exception to an 
otherwise flat tax rate was judged as being not significant enough to earn Zambia a grade of 4, which is  
reserved for countries with a tax system whose top marginal rate is between 36 percent and 45 percent.  
<BR>
[2]  Zambia's average rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 is unavailable. Zambia historically has suffered 
high rates of inflation. 

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
