<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Zimbabwe</TITLE>
<H2>ZIMBABWE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Since its independence from Britain in 1980, Zimbabwe has been a one-party state ruled by 
President Robert Mugabe. Zimbabwe has one of the more industrialized economies in Africa. It is a mixed 
economy in which the government exercises considerable control over economic activity.  Mugabe, 
however, has begun to liberalize the economy somewhat. He is easing restrictions on foreign investment and 
reducing price controls, for example. The future of reform is uncertain because there are powerful elements 
within the government opposed to free markets. 
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Zimbabwe's average tariff rate is 16.6 percent. Customs procedures are complex. Concern over cheaper 
South African imports could lead to more protectionist measures. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4+ (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4+ (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Income is taxed progressively with the top rate at 50 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   
Capital gains are taxed at a 30 percent rate. Tax on corporate income is 42.5 percent. Zimbabwe 
also has a 10 percent to 20 percent capital gains tax and a 10 percent to 20 percent sales tax. 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Government consumption as percentage of GDP is 20.5 percent. The government owns 40 enterprises, 
many of them requiring subsidies. Government-owned enterprises include postal, 
telecommunications, and broadcasting services, railroads and the national air service, all of which 
are closed to private investment.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Zimbabwe's average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 12.5 percent. Inflation was 
approximately 23 percent in 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Prior governmental approval is required for all foreign investment. Foreign investment is discouraged in 
several sectors, including commercial farming and many services. However, foreign investment 
regulations have been substantially liberalized by a 1992 investment code. Investor incentives, 
including duty-free imports in some cases, have been recently introduced. Despite these 
improvements, investor confidence remains low. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Four of five commercial banks are foreign-owned. Foreign commercial and merchant banks are allowed 
majority shareholder status, though this is discouraged. Recent attempts by foreign banks to obtain 
operating licenses have failed. The government, which operates some financial institutions, restricts 
the rates of interest earned by foreign banks. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Some deregulation of prices and lifting of subsidies has occurred. Nevertheless, significant wage and 
price controls remain. The Minister of Labor has sweeping powers to regulate wages.   
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
No nationalization of private property has occurred since independence.  However, in 1990 the 
legislature passed a sweeping land reform bill that enables the government to force the sale of nearly 
half of the remaining white-owned farmland. This land is to be used to establish state-owned 
communal farms.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Prices, wages, and employment are heavily regulated. Government permission is required to terminate 
an employee, for example. The private sector is under increasing pressure to hire and train more 
Zimbabweans. The use of foreign nationals is severely restricted. The bureaucracy is tainted by 
corruption.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Around 20 percent of Zimbabwe's GDP is in the black market. This is caused mainly by government 
monopolies in such areas as transportation services.   
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.50</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]   Zimbabwe's income tax score is based solely on its maximum rate. 


</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
