<title>Institute to hold grand opening gala for national training headquarters</title>
</head>

<body>

<center>
<h2>Institute to hold grand opening gala for national training headquarters</h2>
<I>Supporters invited to join festivities at Steven P. J. Wood Building</I>
</center> 
<P>
<Br>
	<B>BY DAVID J. LINTON</B>
<P>
<DD>	ARLINGTON, VA, July 4  While Independence Day fireworks lit the Washington Monument in bursts of patriotic colors, Leadership Institute staff, interns and friends celebrated and watched from the Jefts Beede Roof Terrace of the new national training headquarters.<BR>  
<DD>	It was the first event in the Institute's new Steven P. J. Wood Building.  And a foretaste of the grand celebration planned for the building's official opening on September 18.<BR>  
<DD>	Megan Lott, a coordinator of the opening event, said, "Although there aren't any fireworks planned for the grand opening, it will certainly have plenty of spark.
<P>
<DD>"It's a time to celebrate the success and growth of the Institute, made possible by <DD>so many generous donors around the world, and to lay the foundation for further <DD>growth," Lott said.
<P>
	Institute president Morton Blackwell said, "Far-seeing donors have made the Institute's past successes possible and will secure its future.   Naturally, I want to show them first hand what their labor has built."
<P> 
<H3>Training headquarters equips conservatives</H3>
<DD>	The new national training headquarters hastens the day when conservative principles of limited government, free market economics, strong national defense and traditional values triumpheven in Washington.
<DD>	The new building enables the Leadership Institute to improve and expand its current programs and train more conservatives.  
<DD>	The building is much more accessible to students and faculty, since it's closer to Washington and only 100 yards from a subway station.  There's even a dorm for out-of-town students.  
<DD>	When classes in the F. M. Kirby National Training Center end each day, students can do their homework in the Elizabeth J. Fitzgerald Study Room or discuss issues in the Norma E. Zimdahl Student Lounge.   
<DD>	The new facility is much more cost-effective and efficient.  The Institute won't have to rent facilities around the city but instead will receive rent from commercial tenants.  
<DD>	More resources will go directly for training.  And Institute staff won't waste time lugging equipment and supplies around Washington.
<P>
<H3>Political technology goes high tech</H3>
<DD>	The new building will provide state-of-the- art computer systems, catapulting the Institute into the 21st century.  
<DD>	For example, each staffer and intern will receive access to a high-speed, shielded computer network.  Each employee will have electronic mail, an internet connection and the ability to search libraries and databases around the world.   
Improved computer technology will enable the Institute to better teach political technology.
<DD>	However, none of these exciting developments would be possible without the generous support of donors, whose gifts continue to allow the Leadership Institute to train young conservatives  to win the battle for our country's future.
<P>
<H3>Donors invited to September grand opening</H3>
<DD>	That's why Morton invites donors to join the celebration of the building's completion at the September 18 grand opening.  
<DD>	Supporters will join the ribbon-cutting ceremony; tour the facilities and meet staff, graduates, faculty and fellow donors.   
<DD>	They'll see first-hand how the building allows the Institute to train more conservatives to effectively fight for the principles of their forefathers.
<DD>	Supporters will have the chance to meet congressional advisory board members and attend a seminar by a national expert on how to maximize personal tax advantages through planned giving. 
<P>
	<I>There will be lots of food and loads of fun.  So come if you can this September 18.</I>
<P>

<DD>	The Institute has arranged special airline and hotel rates.  And the designated hotel will have regular buses that shuttle back and forth between it and the building.  
<DD>	To make travel arrangements at the special rates, please contact Omega Travel at (703)998-2990 or (800)756-6342 as soon as possible. 
<DD>	For more information about the building or how you can attend the dedication, please contact <B>Megan Lott</B> at <B>1-800-827-5323 or 1-703-247-2000.</B>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>


