<html>
<head>
<title>Don Devine "PREPARING FOR THE TRAIN WRECK" -- ACU</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<h2>Preparing For The Train Wreck</h2>
<a href="/townhall/ACU/devine.html">Don Devine</a><br>
The Washington Times -- August 20, 1995
<hr>
</center>
<p>
All Washington is talking about the Fall "train wreck," when
government borrowing authority ends, and the Republican Congress
refuses to pay the bills unless their spending cuts and tax
decreases survive the President's veto. Readers of this space over
the past few months already know that President Bill Clinton has
long been playing the shrewder traffic-management game.
<p>
Top GOP engineer Newt Gingrich now concedes that two key
Contract With America priorities are dead for the year--the line
item veto for the president, and product-liability reforms to limit
the litigation explosion. Of the 21 Contract promises, only three
have become law and most others are in trouble or worse. Senate
Leader Bob Dole, too, has been forced to delay regulatory reform
after three attempts to force moderate Republicans into line. Each
of the 13 appropriations bills has tripped upon major fissures
between moderates and conservatives which, in turn, is exploited by
President Clinton saying this or that is "unfair."
<p>
On most bills, the GOP itself was enough to drive the 1994
revolution off track. Six hundred million additional dollars were
added to House housing appropriations, and a modest loosening of
environmental regulations survived only by a tie vote. The Senate
committee voted to add $815 million more. The House refused to cut
$1.6 billion from the space station. The WIC nutrition program was
increased $260 million. Senator Ted Stevens saved the expensive
helium-cooled graphite reactor. Even an appropriations rider to
eliminate a regulation that only unionized transit could receive
government subsidies--surely a no-brainer for a Republican House--lost 288 to 
186.
<p>
It was all foreseeable. For those interested in the future,
they only need to consult the Rescissions Bill. It was the first
appropriations law entirely the product of the GOP. It claimed $16
billion in cuts, all of which received due attacks in Congress and
from the President for unfairness to some group or other. Now,
seven weeks after President Clinton's veto, $733 million more in
spending demanded by him for education and training allowed him to
sign. But $7 billion was also added for new projects, so total
spending was reduced only $9 billion.
<p>
The Republicans could claim credit for cutting spending. Bill
Clinton could crow: "This is how we should work together. We agree
we should balance the budget. We disagree on how. But this shows we
can work together." The GOP took months of criticism for being
unfair to children, the poor, the ill, infirm, old, women and the
environment, among others. Then the President restored the "unfair"
cuts and it all turned out ok. It is no coincidence the President's
standing in the polls improved. As predicted here, his strategy is
to concede the Republican agenda to balance the budget, even the
necessity for spending cuts; but to argue that a Democratic
president is necessary to assure the cuts are not too extreme.
<p>
Each chamber of Congress has thirteen appropriations bills
scheduled to pass through the same process before the train wreck
of the Reconciliation Bill. The president or his representatives
have already threatened to veto seven. At this rate, presidential
approval may hit the 60 percent mark. It already hit 50 percent,
and showed Bill Clinton defeating any Republican, even with Jesse
Jackson in the race. It is time to question whose train will wreck.
The conventional wisdom is that Mr. Clinton does not have Ronald
Reagan's stomach for a fight that would shut down the government.
The rescissions example suggests he does not have to have much
intestinal fortitude to claim he made things "better."
<p>
The other possibility is for the GOP to stop playing Snively
Whiplash to Mr. Clinton's Dudley DoRight. The first thing that
needs to be done is to stop the appropriations locomotives in their
tracks. The Democrats did the last time. Why take multiple hits for
every small change over the next few months? Why focus the media on
each appropriations bill in sequence as each reaches the floor for
its own vote and own time on nightly TV, "unfairness" horror
stories and all? Better the confusion of 26 bills moving at the
same time and not converging until the Reconciliation Bill itself.
Then throw Medicaid and Medicare into the mix too, with only modest
changes before 1997. Take the heat and glory together. If there is
going to be a train wreck, why not make it a big one?
<p>
What should the Republicans in Congress be doing in the
meantime? They should raise a "fairness" issue of their own. Before
his major policy speech on affirmative action, White House
officials told the Washington Times that President Clinton would
"insist, as have a generation of politicians, that quotas are not
the same as setting 'goals and timetables' to assist minorities in
hiring and promotion." The "goal" is to make "as few changes as
possible." As the speech showed, Mr. Clinton says "mend it, don't
end it," but retains the same goals and timetables--and still
insists they are not quotas. In other words, the same unfairness of
quotas remains national policy. The Republicans should accept the
challenge. These programs exist in enough different forms and in so
many agencies that hearings could be held in almost every committee
of Congress, to discuss the issue of fairness fully, in a manner
the media could not ignore.
<p>
Jesse Jackson could do his part to lead the national debate on
fairness in employment. There is a project sponsored by the U.S.
Conference of Mayors called CityVote that will be an informal
"primary" for presidential candidates to give "disenfranchised
urban dwellers a real voice in the process," according to Mayor
Larry Agran. It will be held November 7, a full 100 days before the
New Hampshire primary. What better forum for Mr. Jackson to debate
the issue with Mr. Clinton, and have the possibility of winning the
following test vote? With a poll showing the President could win
with Mr. Jackson in the race as a third party candidate, this turns
from a partisan to a classic issues debate. Rather than speculate
about train wrecks, we could have a real national debate on the
very fundamental issue, what is fairness in employment?
<p>
[ <a href="/townhall/ACU/i-col.html">ACU Columnists</a> ]
<p>
</body>
</html>
