<title>Grace-Marie Arnett - Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<h3>GRACE-MARIE ARNETT</h3>
<hr>
<b>Vice President for Information Marketing</b>
<P><IMG SRC="/heritage/staff/pics/arnett.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
<P>
Grace-Marie Arnett is vice president for information marketing at The Heritage Foundation. 
<p>
	Arnett oversees Heritage's marketing research activities and assists other departments at Heritage in developing, implementing and coordinating strategies to reach new and broader audiences with their research, publications and programs. 
<p> She also has direct responsibility for overseeing and expanding Heritage's electronic communications activities, including its presence on <a href="http://www.townhall.com">Town Hall</a>, the Internet "web page for conservatives." And she will oversee the production, distribution, and sale of <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/townhall_shop/">Heritage publications</a>.  
<P>	Arnett previously operated the consulting firm Arnett & Co., which specialized in public policy analysis. She also served as executive director of the <a href="http://www.townhall.com/taxcom">National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform</a> -- "the Kemp Commission" -- chaired by former congressman and Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp. Heritage President <a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Edwin Feulner</a> served as vice chairman of the commission. Earlier this year, Arnett was a senior policy advisor to the Forbes for President campaign.
<p>	Arnett has written extensively on tax and health policy and is a founding member of the Consensus Group, an affiliation of health policy experts who advance market-based approaches to reform. She is a frequent guest on radio and television programs and has had articles published in the <I>Washington Post, Wall Street Journal</I>, and numerous other journals and newspapers. 
<p>	Before starting her consulting firm, Arnett was a journalist and won numerous awards for her news and analytical articles on politics and public policy. In 1989 she received the Marion Chase Memorial Award for Public Service from the D.C. Mental Health Association and the Washington Psychiatric Society for her work in the mental health field. 
<p>	A native of Albuquerque, N.M, Arnett resides in Alexandria, Va. She holds a bachelor of arts degree from the University of New Mexico. 
<p>
