<head>
<title>The Right Staff</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<H2>Find a job, or offer a job to conservatives through the Employment Placement Service</H2>
</center>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>By Jay Hopkins</B>
<P>
	<I>All that conservatives must do to win is elect those who share their values, right?<BR>
	Unfortunately, no.<BR> </I>
<P>	
<DD>	Elected officials come and go.  But staff may stay a lifetime.  Agency bureaucrats, Capitol Hill staffers and Gucci-shod lobbyists are the permanent ruling class of Washington. Some of them have more influence on legislation than many individual congressmen.    
<DD>	It's no secret that most Washington staff are liberal.  Or that they've grown comfortable with their power and perks.  Since they know full well that conservative government reform would end many of their careers in power, they use every trick in the book to resist real reform. 
<DD>	Morton Blackwell, president of the Leadership Institute, prescribes a treatment for Washington's plague of liberal staff:  replace them with conservatives.	
<DD>	That's why the Leadership Institute's Employment Placement Service (EPS) works to place committed and skilled conservatives in positions of influence on Capitol Hill, in government agencies, in think tanks and in the media. 
<DD>	The Employment Placement Service literally changes the culture of Washington.  Each year, EPS places scores of sound conservatives.  And thanks to generous Institute donors, EPS provides this vital service free of charge to both employer and job-seeker.
<DD>	"The Employment Placement Service is head and shoulders above other job placement programs in its quality of service.  It provides reliable and clear information about excellent candidates," said Mark Mix, vice-president for legislation at the National Right to Work Committee.  "I go to EPS whenever I have a position to fill."
<DD>	The placement service has earned a strong reputation among job-seekers, as well.  Heather Farish, who recently found a job through EPS, wrote,  "I had been told by three separate individuals the Leadership Institute is a good place to go to find a job.  But I never expected to see results in just two days."
<DD>	"All I did was fill out the application and have an interview with the placement director.  The next thing I knew, my phone started ringing.  I lined up a few interviews and was hired the next day.  Thanks for all your hard work," Farish said. 
<DD>	While EPS can't find every conservative job-seeker a public policy position in two days, the staff do go out of their way to assist in any way they can.   For example, staff help to fine-tune resumes to better market them to public policy employers.
<DD>	One person who benefited from the advice wrote,  "In just a few minutes over the telephone, I believe we improved my resume ten-fold.  I appreciate the helping hand."
<DD>	In addition to directly placing conservatives in public policy jobs, EPS also helps job-seekers to improve their chances to find a job through their own efforts.  Following a personal interview, one job-seeker wrote, "Wow! You really helped me focus my job-hunting strategy."
<DD>	Mark Montini, Leadership Institute vice-president for programs, said,  "EPS staff know what it's like to be out there looking for a job.  In order to help as many qualified people as possible, they work tirelessly to find new and more creative ways of getting employers' attention." 
<DD>	A new and innovative monthly fax newsletter aimed at employers is a case in point.  The newsletter highlights the qualifications of several individuals.  Employers are encouraged to contact EPS for more information on those and other job-seekers.
<DD>	Increasingly, EPS succeeds with its creative outreach.  Busy employers appreciate the fact that a simple phone call to EPS can get them carefully targeted resumes, usually within 24 hours.  And some employers even have EPS conduct reference and background checks on resumes they have on hand.
<DD>	Already, more than a few Capitol Hill offices and conservative organizations rely exclusively on EPS's free service to fill job openings.  Through EPS placements, conservative influence in public policy grows each day.
<DD>	Thanks to the many Leadership Institute supporters who share Morton's vision of principled conservatives in public policy, the time is nigh when government once again is the servant rather than the master of the people.
<P>
<BR>
<B>Jay Hopkins is Employment Placement Service director.  For information, to receive an application or to advertise a job opening, please call him at (800)827-5323 or (703)247-2000.</B>
<P>
